Venezuela's Chavez calls oil prices fair

http://thestar.com.my/news/story...131&amp;sec=apworld

A day after urging OPEC leaders to cut oil production, Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez defended soaring world oil prices as fair and lambasted the United States for excessive energy consumption.

"The big consumers say that oil is very expensive," Chavez said Friday. "No, oil is not expensive. It's only that oil is a nonrenewable natural resource and they have to learn to conserve."

Analysts say the leftist Chavez's political ideals may not be shared by fellow OPEC members, but Thursday's meeting gave him a chance to raise his profile internationally while offering some economic suggestions that appeared to resonate.

Speaking to supporters, Chavez scolded wealthy countries for what he called blatant wastefulness and said capitalism is the root of the problem. The United States, he said, amassed fortunes by taking millions of barrels of low-priced oil out of Venezuela the same way Spanish conquerers once made off with gold.

"There have been 500 years of looting, and here's the result: countries in the North are developed and we are poor here," he said. "Misery, death, infant mortality, sickness and illiteracy pervades the countries of the South.

"They call oil 'black gold.' Of course, they first looted our gold, silver, precious stones and so many other things, then the oil. Venezuela is saying 'Enough!'"
